getty.ScopeNote:
Area of modern Egypt comprises the core of the ancient kingdom of
                        Egypt; area was home to Neolithic cultures by 6000 BCE; Thinite dynasty
                        united Upper and Lower Egypt ca. 3100 BCE; important Hellenistic center;
                        part of Roman Empire until Arab conquest in 640, then Mameluk and Ottoman;
                        official language is Arabic, though English and French are also widely
                        spoken.

Area comprising modern Baden-Würtemmberg, Hesse and western Bavaria;
                        originally settled by Suevi and Alemanni; taken by Franks in 5th century CE;
                        powerful medieval duchy from 10th century; ruled by Hohenstaufen kings and
                        emperors; bound in league of cities, 14-16th centuries.

Said to be first Roman colony beyond the Alps, founded in 118 BCE;
                        taken by Visigoths in 412, by Saracens in 719 and by Pepin the Short in 759;
                        flourished as manufacturing city 11th-12th centuries; boulevards replaced
                        medieval fortifications by 1870; site of 11th- and 14th-century
                        church.

Located on Tyrrhenian Sea; founded by Trajan as port for Rome;
                        flourished in late Roman era; sacked by Vandals, then Saracens (828);
                        inhabitants moved to nearby mountains, but later returned to old site; walls
                        strengthened in 16th cen.; damaged in WW II.

Fortified by Romans; sacked by Attila 5th cen.; prospered as free
                        imperial city 13th cen.; taken by French along with Tour & Verdun 1552;
                        surrendered to Germans in 1870 & was under German rule 1871-1918;
                        reverted to France after World War I.

Nation's easternmost town; retained Greek language until 11th cen.;
                        was important trade center with Orient until razed by Turks in 1480; supply
                        base during WW II; scene of Horace Walpole's novel The Castle of Otranto;
                        connected by hydrofoil to Corfu.

Located N of modern Caserta; site of battle during First Samnite War
                        (343 BCE); during Middle Ages, Suésula was part of the duchy of Benevento;
                        destroyed by Saracens 880 CE.

Located on Gulf of Taranto; founded by Achaean Greeks; was powerful
                        & rich, famous for Olympic athletes from 588 BCE; established democracy;
                        defeated by the Bruttii, Syracuse & Epirus; Roman from 3rd cen. BCE;
                        modern city was part of Kingdom of Naples.

A Massalian trading post in ancient times; later taken by Visigoths;
                        an episcopal see from 400 to 1790, when it was secularized during the French
                        Revolution.
